Old students of the Lagos Baptist Secondary School, Agege, Lagos, has called on Nigerians to invest in their alma mater. Speaking at the commissioning of the school’s renovated Biology Laboratory, president of the 1979 to 1984 set, Dr Aina Odusola, said the gesture was a means of giving back to their alma mater. He, thereby, implored other olds students to emulate their gesture. “The projects being commissioned today include the refurbishing of the Biology Laboratory, supply of the school library with current textbooks and the upgrading of the Information Communication Technology centre with 20 units of desktop computers and accessories.” “I implore other sets and old students to also emulate this gesture. We need more of this. We can’t leave everything to the government. Everyone should inculcate the culture of coming back to give to their alma mater.” He noted that two scholarships would be given to best students who wished to study Medicine and Law in any Nigerian University, saying, it would commence in 2022 session. Principal, Lagos Baptist Senior Secondary School, Mr Kolawole Sofolahan, said, “I want to thank you all,  looking at the economic situation of Nigeria, it is not easy coming together to make financial commitment as this.” An old student, Dr Bolaji Akinyemi, advised the students to be focused  and diligent. “You may look at yourself as small but you are not small. Don’t be distracted, do not allow peer pressure take away your future,” he said. Leke Mogaji also said, “We came together a year ago, this is the beginning. I learnt a lot from this school and nobody should count anyone out, there is greatness in everyone.”.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com